<article>
    <h1>PER&#xAD;SPEC&#xAD;TIVES FILM FES&#xAD;TI&#xAD;VAL</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201016/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-10-16"><time>2020-10-16</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE | HAPPENINGS</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>Sin­ga­pore’s first and long­est stu­dent-run fes­ti­val re­turns with an all-on­line pro­gramme of eight films.</p>
    <p>The films are cho­sen be­cause they re­flect this year’s theme of truth and how it is ma­nip­u­lated by those who take im­ages or text out of con­text.</p>
    <p>Among them is the doc­u­men­tary Feels Good Man (NC16, 92 min­utes, avail­able from Oct 23). Direc­tor Arthur Jones looks into Pepe The Frog (right), a car­toon that first ap­peared in a 2005 on­line comic, but which has since been ap­pro­pri­ated by far-right and white su­prem­a­cist groups for use in hate memes – a di­rec­tion that has ap­palled the im­age’s cre­ator, Matt Furie.</p>
    <p>The film won the US Doc­u­men­tary Spe­cial Award at the Sun­dance Film Fes­ti­val this year.</p>
    <p>WHERE: www.per­spec­tives­film­fes­ti­val.com</p>
    <p>WHEN: Oct 23 till Nov 1</p>
    <p>AD­MIS­SION: $8 for a 48-hour view­ing win­dow.</p>
    <p>Dis­counted bun­dles are avail­able</p>

